 Driving American foreign policy, Gonzalez argues, is a domestic system of urban sprawl based on the automobile and the energy reserves necessary to maintain it. The massive consumer demand created by urban sprawl underpins US foreign policy in the Middle East, while concerns over access to energy drive the European Union project.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aCities and townsxGrowth. 0aGeopoliticsxUnited States. 0aGeopoliticszUnited States. 0aPower resourcesxEurope. 0aPower resourcesxUnited States. 0aPower resourceszEurope. 0aPower resourceszUnited States. 4aEnvironmental Studies : Environmental Politics. 4aHistory : American History. 4aHistory : European History. 4aPolitics and Law : International Relations. 4aPublic Policy : Energy Policy. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh1 aLatimer, Christopher P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781438447964?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438447964423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438447964/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles